   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "87f4aa9a-10c2-46ed-a4f9-5f0a418ade30",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 1: Select data\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1a) Grab location of interest by latitude and longitude\n",
    "First we'll grab heat index timeseries for a specific location of interest (the Fresno Airport weather station (KFAT)). We will **not** be retrieving the actual station data that is bias-corrected to that station for this example. At present, bias-corrected station data on the Analytics Engine only provides air temperature as a variable, and for Heat Index we must also have either dew point temperature or relative humidity. So for the time being, we will retrieve **non-bias corrected** data at the location of interest.\n",
    "\n",
    "For this analysis, it is crucial to use the `convert_to_local_time` process as shown below. The dynamically downscaled WRF data in the Cal-Adapt: Analytics Engine uses UTC time. Using the local time is particularly important for determining the timing of the daily maximum and minimum temperatures. For a station located in Pacific Time (US), UTC time places the daily minimum \"in\" the day prior because UTC is 8 hours ahead of Pacific! The handy `convert_to_local_time` process corrects for this and ensures that the resulting high and low temperatures are within the same daily timestamp.  \n",
    "\n",
    "Note: For demonstration purposes we are selecting only ten years of data. We recomend using a longer period (at least 30 years) for conducting a scientific analysis."
   ]
  },
