   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c9aba87f-6b92-45f0-9546-a3ff1f6f5103",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 2: Calculate the number of hours throughout the year above a threshold\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2a) Sum the hours per day\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's next determine what part of the day is above a Heat Index threshold, as well as how many hours in each day are above our designated threshold. The NOAA Heat Index  \"kicks in\" once the [NOAA Heat Index](https://www.noaa.gov/sites/default/files/2022-05/heatindex_chart_rh.pdf) value is above 80°F: prolonged exposure to a Heat Index above 80°F becomes dangerous to many people and especially vulnerable communities. The Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) uses the Heat Index as a screening tool in the [NIOSH/OSHA Heat App](https://www.osha.gov/heat/heat-app) to indicate the risk of heat-related illness and protections for outdoor workers. The OSHA screening categories are shown below. We note that these values are slightly different than those used by the [NOAA Heat Index](https://www.noaa.gov/sites/default/files/2022-05/heatindex_chart_rh.pdf) system. We **strongly recommend** looking at multiple thresholds to understand Heat Index trends. \n",
    "\n",
    "| Classification | Heat Index |\n",
    "|----------------|------------|\n",
    "| Caution | <80°F |\n",
    "| Warning | 80 - 94°F |\n",
    "| Danger | 95+°F |\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll start with 80°F as our default threshold, putting these results in the OSHA \"Caution\" category."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "06780bc5-9344-4265-9ff7-b80cc43cf5c1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "hi_threshold = 80"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "8f9f3f6f-0242-4dfd-9d87-9a6f813a13d0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# counts the number of hours in each day above the heat index threshold\n",
    "num_heatidx_histhours = (heatidx_hist_hour >= hi_threshold).resample(time=\"1D\").sum()\n",
    "num_heatidx_histhours = num_heatidx_histhours.rename(\n",
    "    f\"Hours per day above Heat Index threshold of {hi_threshold}°F\"\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
